result.execSummary:
The defendant Cheryl M. Dunneisen was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property-Special Facts, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Cases 16CF5,16CM188, 16CM190 called together at 10:34am [ma]
Defendant Cheryl M. Dunneisen in court with attorney Elizabeth F Svehlek.  Susan Victoria Happ appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
  
Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; pleas of " NO CONTEST " entered on Count #2 of Case 16CF5, Count #1 of Case 16CM188 and Count #1 of Case 16CM190; factual basis stipulated; the Court accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

DA Happ verifies victim rights compliance; submits victim impact statements; notes victims from misdemeanor cases are present and wish to address the Court. 

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses: all remaining counts
Sentencing arguments given by DA Happ
Statement made by Francine and Jeffrey Grise
Sentencing argument given by Atty. Svehlek
Statement made by Ms. Dunneisen

On Count #2 of Case 16CF5, the Court withholds sentence, and places Defendant on Probation for 3 years.

On Count #1 of Case 16CM188, the Court withholds sentence, and places Defendant on Probation for 2 years.

On Count #1 of Case 16CM190, the Court withholds sentence, and places Defendant on Probation for 2 years.

Conditions of Probation:
--On Case 16CM188: to serve 30 days in the Jefferson County Jail, with work-release privileges for employment, treatment, counseling and therapy, to commence on 10/16/16 at 6:00pm.
---Ms. Dunneisen is required to report for commencement and service of jail sentence with absolute sobriety and without non-prescribed controlled substances in system; non-compliance will result in loss of work-release privileges without further process.

--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with recommended treatment per Agent
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment or counseling as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--to attempt to obtain/maintain employment and/or education program as approved by the Agent
--no contact with Andrew Grunewald, except for child care and family court as authorized by the Agent
--no presence in any bar, tavern, or liquor store
--not to be present in any casino, or other establishment where the primary source of income is gambling
--maintain absolute sobriety
--not to possess alcohol or illegal drugs 
--to pay statutory costs
--As to Case 16CM188: to pay restitution in the amount of $2900 to Jeff and Francine Grise
--As to Case 16CM190: to pay restitution in the amount of $2900 to Jeff and Francine Grise
--As to Case 16CF5: to pay restitution in the amount of $540 to Andrew Grunewald

Days credit for time already served:  1  day as to 16CF05; all other cases 0 days credit.
